The paper discusses network capacity theorems and coding arguments, which are typically studied in the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions distributed computation over noisy channels, which falls under the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DS) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of structured codes for practical constructions, which is relevant to the Security and Cryptography (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions multicasting and multiple-access networks, which are topics studied in the Computer Communications (cs.CC) sub-category.
